“I want to ensure that we are going to provide enough security in the upcoming by-election. As the governor (Kwale’s Salim Mvurya) said that the election would come and go. We should all consider that by being conducting a peaceful exercise,” said Dr Matiang’i.
Dr Matiang’i was accompanied by Mr Mvurya who urged fellow politicians to conduct peaceful campaigns ahead of the next week by-election.
Campaigns for the by-elections have heightened following the presence of Mombasa Governor Hassan Joho who is drumming up support for ODM party candidate Omar Boga.





Mr Mvurya is supporting independent candidate Feisal Bader who is also backed by Deputy President William Ruto. The two governors have been trading barbs in the heated campaigns.
Yesterday, while accompanying Dr Matiang’i, Mr Mvurya said there was need for politicians who are conducting their campaigns to base them on uniting people.
“We want everyone to coordinate with the security officers who will be providing security for us during the by-election. This by-election should not be a reason for tension in our county. The polls will come and go,” he said.
He said the residents of Kwale have co-existed without any form of discrimination and “we as politicians should ensure we observe that. We should avoid anything that will bring division amongst us”.



